      Tesla $1 trillion
   =20
 =20
Imagine how much sadder Elon Musk would be today if he had managed to take =
Tesla Inc. private in 2018. In August 2018,  he tweeted =E2=80=9Cconsiderin=
g taking Tesla private at $420. Funding secured,=E2=80=9D and spent a few d=
ays pretending it might happen. Eventually he decided not to do it, because=
 (1) in fact he had no funding and (2) it would not have been possible to t=
ake Tesla private=C2=A0and keep all of its public shareholders, which for s=
ome reason is something that Musk said he wanted to do. It was all pretty h=
alf-baked, and later Musk  got in trouble with the Securities and Exchange =
Commission because pretending you=E2=80=99re going to buy out a public comp=
any is something of a no-no.But imagine he=E2=80=99d done it; imagine he ha=
d taken umpteen billion dollars of  Saudi sovereign wealth money and bought=
 out all of Tesla=E2=80=99s public shareholders, leaving himself and the Sa=
udis as the only owners.[1] In some sense, it would have been an incredible=
 trade. Tesla=E2=80=99s stock=C2=A0closed at $341.99 the day before Musk tw=
eeted that he=E2=80=99d buy it for $420. It closed yesterday at $1,034.07. =
In between there was a 5-for-1 stock split. The stock is up=C2=A0more than =
1,100% from Musk=E2=80=99s proposed deal price in about three years. Yester=
day=E2=80=99s closing price gave Tesla a market capitalization of $1.03 tri=
llion.=C2=A0In hindsight, Musk would have been buying the company cheap:[2]=
On the other hand. Since August 2018, Tesla has done four stock offerings r=
aising a total of more than $13 billion, which it has used to, you know, ma=
ke cars and become huge. Would it have been able to go back to its private =
backers for $13 billion of capital after doing the largest leveraged buyout=
 in history? Maybe, I don=E2=80=99t know; private markets were pretty gener=
ous for much of that time. But the public market=C2=A0was=C2=A0extremely=C2=
=A0generous to Tesla. The last two of those offerings, for $5 billion each,=
 were  at-the-market offerings to Musk=E2=80=99s horde of retail-investor f=
ans; one of them was timed to Tesla=E2=80=99s addition to the S&P 500 index=
. You can=E2=80=99t do a retail at-the-market offering, or an index-add off=
ering,=C2=A0with a private company. Tesla's cost of capital is incredibly, =
incredibly low, because it raises money not from a handful of professional =
private equity investors but from an army of Tesla enthusiasts. It is good =
to have a low cost of capital if you are in a capital-intensive business.Ev=
en more important, look, Elon Musk runs a trillion-dollar company. If he ha=
d taken it private, he would be running a company that he bought for $80-od=
d=C2=A0billion in 2018 and that had improved its financial performance sinc=
e then. How much would it be worth? Who knows? It wouldn=E2=80=99t trade pu=
blicly. Retail investors couldn=E2=80=99t bid up the price. It would be wor=
th some vague amount north of $80 billion. =E2=80=9CIf Musk were to take Te=
sla public again,=E2=80=9D analysts might write, =E2=80=9Che might be able =
to get as much as a $400 billion valuation,=E2=80=9D or whatever. Might som=
eone have written =E2=80=9Che might be able to get $1 trillion=E2=80=9D? Su=
re, why not. But that wouldn=E2=80=99t be an accepted fact. The value of Te=
sla would be some unknown number because it wouldn=E2=80=99t trade. Who wou=
ld believe it was $1 trillion?Today Bloomberg=E2=80=99s billionaire list te=
lls me that Musk is the richest person in the world, with a net worth of $2=
88.6 billion, consisting mostly of Tesla stock. Jeff Bezos is in second pla=
ce with $192.6 billion of mostly Amazon.com Inc. stock. Musk was well behin=
d Bezos last year, but he=E2=80=99s up $118.9 billion year-to-date, because=
 Tesla=E2=80=99s stock has been on a tear. No public stock, no tear, no =E2=
=80=9Crichest person on Earth.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s nice to be the richest=
 person on earth! I assume.Of course in some sense he=E2=80=99d be=C2=A0eco=
nomically=C2=A0 just as rich as he is now (richer, really), because he=E2=
=80=99d control just as much (more, really) of the same company making the =
same cars; maybe he=E2=80=99d even be able to make better business decision=
s freed from the pressures of the public market, and revenue would be even =
higher. But nobody would=C2=A0know about it. There=E2=80=99d be no scoreshe=
et saying that he=E2=80=99s worth $288.6 billion. The value to Elon Musk of=
 public markets is partly that they allow him to raise limitless capital to=
 fund his business, but it=E2=80=99s mostly that they allow everyone to kee=
p score of how rich and successful he is. Private-market success is quieter=
. I do not think that Elon Musk likes quiet.People love to complain about t=
he myopia and short-termism of public markets. Elon Musk, in particular,  u=
sed to love to complain about that, which is why he briefly pretended he wa=
s going to take Tesla private. There is probably some truth to some of thes=
e complaints.=C2=A0But there is maybe no better counterexample in the histo=
ry of capitalism=C2=A0than Tesla. Elon Musk had a dream of making electric =
cars cool and ubiquitous, and that dream was pretty far out there, and he s=
pent years missing production targets and losing money in pursuit of that d=
ream, and his legions of public-market fans patiently funded him, and it tu=
rns out that he and they were right and now you can  rent a Tesla at a Hert=
z. And the stock market has rewarded him with hysterical lavishness, giving=
 his company a bigger valuation than every other car company combined=C2=A0=
and making him the richest person in the world. Imagine if he had given all=
 that up to go private! He really dodged a bullet. Meanwhile:If you were wo=
ndering which junk-rated company would be the first to reach a trillion-dol=
lar market capitalization, your wait is over. It=E2=80=99s Tesla Inc.=C2=A0=
The automaker=E2=80=99s debt may still be considered speculative-grade, but=
 its stock passed the $1 trillion mark on Monday, according to data compile=
d by Bloomberg. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThe $1 trillion mark leaves Tesla c=
reditors with unprecedented equity cushion for a junk-rated issuer,=E2=80=
=9D said Bloomberg Intelligence credit analyst Joel Levington.The =E2=80=9C=
equity cushion=E2=80=9D idea is a  somewhat strange way to think about cred=
itworthiness but it does seem obviously true here. Bloomberg tells me that =
Tesla has about $10 billion of total debt. If Musk ever wanted to pay that =
off he could go to the stock market and raise $10 billion in an hour; the s=
tock would probably go=C2=A0up. That has to make his creditors feel good.
