      Bank debt
   =20
 =20
One stylized fact about the current economy is that  banks have too much mo=
ney. People and companies have lots of cash and want to store it somewhere,=
 so they put it in bank deposits. Because they have so much cash, they do n=
ot need to borrow much cash, so there is not a ton of demand for bank loans=
. Banks are left with lots of deposits and no loans to invest them in. They=
 dislike this situation and try to avoid it by, for instance, lowering inte=
rest rates on deposits below zero, or just asking customers to cool it with=
 the deposits. But there is only so much they can do.Two important stylized=
 facts about bank deposits are (1) they can be withdrawn at any time and (2=
) a dollar in the bank has to always be worth a dollar. If you have money i=
n a checking account, you can go to the bank and ask for it back, and they =
have to be able to give it to you in full immediately. If they can=E2=80=99=
t, then the banking system is in bad trouble. This is the =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=
=99s a Wonderful Life=E2=80=9D problem, and modern banking regulation is de=
signed to prevent it. In particular:=09There is=C2=A0capital=C2=A0regulatio=
n=C2=A0(as well as =E2=80=9Csupplementary leverage ratio=E2=80=9D and =E2=
=80=9Ctotal loss-absorbing capacity=E2=80=9D rules), which requires banks t=
o fund a certain percentage of their assets with shareholders=E2=80=99 equi=
ty (or bonds, for TLAC) so that, if the assets lose value, the shareholders=
 lose money first and the depositors are protected.=09There are=C2=A0net st=
able funding=C2=A0rules, which, to oversimplify, require banks to fund a ce=
rtain percentage of their assets with=C2=A0long-term=C2=A0obligations (stoc=
k, bonds, etc.) so that they don=E2=80=99t get asked for all of their money=
 back at once.These rules make a lot of sense in an =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a=
 Wonderful Life=E2=80=9D world, or in the world of the 2008 financial crisi=
s, when banks had thin capital cushions and lots of short-term non-deposit =
liabilities (repo, etc.) that led to surprising bank-run-type situations.Bu=
t these rules are a little weird in a world where people keep shoveling cas=
h into bank deposits and banks, not having enough loans to make,=C2=A0shove=
l the cash into Treasury securities or reserves at the Federal Reserve. One=
 reason that they=E2=80=99re weird is that, when a bank gets $100 of deposi=
ts and puts the $100 into Fed reserves, its risk (of a capital loss or bank=
 run) hasn=E2=80=99t really gone up any, so it=E2=80=99s weird that these r=
isk-mitigating measures kick in.[3]But another reason they=E2=80=99re weird=
 is that, when banks get too much money, that=C2=A0forces them to raise mor=
e money. If you have a bank with assets consisting of $100 of loans and lia=
bilities of $10 of equity capital (10% of assets), $10 of long-term bonds (=
20% long-term funding including equity and bonds),=C2=A0and $80 of deposits=
, and then all of a sudden you get $300 more of deposits and park them in T=
reasuries, now your equity capital is only 2.5% of assets and you are under=
capitalized and need to sell stock, and your long-term funding ratio is als=
o too low and you need to sell some bonds.=C2=A0Here=E2=80=99s a fun Wall S=
treet Journal story about how banks are rushing to issue bonds because they=
 have too much money:U.S. banks are overrun with cash. So they are loading =
up on debt. =E2=80=A6The record debt sales might seem unnecessary because b=
anks are already up to their eyeballs in cash. The biggest consumer and com=
mercial banks have collected trillions of dollars of deposits since the pan=
demic started.But deposits are only one part of the liability equation for =
the biggest banks. They are also required to keep a certain share of their =
liabilities in long-term debt. Because of that, the ratio of debt to other =
liabilities can get out of whack when deposits grow as much as they have. S=
o banks are issuing more bonds to navigate the regulatory hurdles.Requireme=
nts that long-term debt make up a minimum share of banks=E2=80=99 liabiliti=
es is a consequence of regulations after the financial crisis of 2008-09. T=
he idea is that a layer of long-term debt makes banks less susceptible to p=
anic in short-term funding markets, which was a key reason for the demise o=
f Lehman Brothers.As problems with the banking system go, =E2=80=9Cbanks ha=
ve too much money so they have to raise more money=E2=80=9D is considerably=
 nicer than the more traditional and=C2=A0scarier =E2=80=9Cbanks have too l=
ittle money so they have to raise more money.=E2=80=9D This is more of a we=
ird problem than a bad problem. It is weird though.
