      Good advice
   =20
 =20
This  is great:Chinese authorities told billionaire Hui Ka Yan to use his p=
ersonal wealth to alleviate China Evergrande Group=E2=80=99s deepening debt=
 crisis, according to people familiar with the matter.Beijing=E2=80=99s dir=
ective to the Evergrande founder came after his company missed an initial S=
ept. 23 deadline for a coupon payment on a dollar bond, said the people, as=
king not to be identified discussing a private matter. Local governments ac=
ross China are monitoring Evergrande=E2=80=99s bank accounts to ensure comp=
any cash is used to complete unfinished housing projects and not diverted t=
o pay creditors, the people said.It=E2=80=99s unclear whether Hui=E2=80=99s=
 fortune is big and liquid enough to make a sizable dent in Evergrande=E2=
=80=99s liabilities, which swelled to more than $300 billion as of June. =
=E2=80=A6Hui=E2=80=99s net worth has dwindled to about $7.8 billion from $4=
2 billion at its peak in 2017, according to Bloomberg Billionaires Index es=
timates. But the figure comes with considerable uncertainty.=C2=A0Much of H=
ui=E2=80=99s known wealth is derived from his controlling stake in Evergran=
de and the cash dividends he=E2=80=99s received from the company since its =
2009 listing in Hong Kong. Hui has pocketed about $8 billion over the past =
decade thanks to Evergrande=E2=80=99s generous payouts, according to Bloomb=
erg calculations. It=E2=80=99s not known how Hui reinvested those dividends=
.I do think that the concept of limited corporate liability is a bit porous=
=C2=A0if you=E2=80=99re a Chinese billionaire. In America, if=C2=A0you=C2=
=A0run a company with $300 billion in debt, and it can=E2=80=99t pay that d=
ebt, and you have $8 billion sitting in your personal bank account,=C2=A0yo=
u say =E2=80=9Cah I wish I could do something for all of my company=E2=80=
=99s creditors but unfortunately my deep commitment to our capitalist econo=
mic system prevents me from paying debts that aren=E2=80=99t mine, my hands=
 are really tied here.=E2=80=9D That is so deeply the American way that Don=
ald Trump did it repeatedly and was elected president for his troubles.In C=
hina, if you run a company with $300 billion of debt, and it can=E2=80=99t =
pay that debt, and you have $8 billion sitting in your personal bank accoun=
t, and the government calls you up to say =E2=80=9Chey spend down your bank=
 account to pay that debt,=E2=80=9D the=C2=A0only possible answer=C2=A0is =
=E2=80=9Cyes, that=E2=80=99s what I was already doing, of course, I would n=
ever take $8 billion and run and leave my creditors holding the bag.=E2=80=
=9D Whether or not you signed a personal guarantee, you signed a personal g=
uarantee.Temperamentally I tend to be a big fan of limited liability, but I=
 do think that there is something to be said for each system.I don=E2=80=99=
t know how much Hui ransacking his couch cushions for spare change will act=
ually help with Evergrande=E2=80=99s $300 billion of debt, but=C2=A0I suppo=
se if he has cashed out $8 billion then he probably has enough money to pay=
 off a $100 million interest payment here, a $200 million maturity there. I=
f this is more =E2=80=9Cbridging a temporary liquidity problem=E2=80=9D tha=
n it is =E2=80=9Cthrowing money into the ocean of a catastrophic default,=
=E2=80=9D maybe his personal fortune will help. But even if it doesn=E2=80=
=99t help and Evergrande does default, it is probably wise for him, persona=
lly and politically, not to end up with too much money.
