      Aramco emissions
   =20
 =20
Okay:Saudi Aramco, the world=E2=80=99s biggest exporter of oil, set a goal =
of reaching net-zero emissions from its wholly-owned operations by 2050.The=
 target excludes emissions from customers burning its crude, but is a decad=
e sooner than a government timetable for the kingdom. ...The pledge applies=
 to emissions from the company=E2=80=99s own operations or from the generat=
ion of power and heat to its assets, classified as Scope 1 and Scope 2. It =
doesn=E2=80=99t apply to Scope 3, which are generated by customers burning =
its fuels and make up more than 80% of the company=E2=80=99s total emission=
s.I assume that the world will eventually reach an equilibrium in which (1)=
 every single company, government, person, etc., can certify that they have=
 net zero carbon emissions, but (2) the world keeps emitting carbon. (For i=
nstance, every tree on earth will be sold multiple times to carbon emitters=
 to offset their carbon, etc.) =E2=80=9CMust be aliens,=E2=80=9D people wil=
l say.There is actually a weird sort of accounting logic here. People under=
stand that oil companies contribute a lot to climate change. Oil companies =
are, therefore, a focus for environmental criticism. =E2=80=9CDo stuff for =
the climate,=E2=80=9D activists say, to oil companies. =E2=80=9COkay we wil=
l be net zero emitters, eventually,=E2=80=9D the oil companies say. =E2=80=
=9CSure we will drill oil and sell it to people, but=C2=A0our=C2=A0activiti=
es will be totally clean; what our customers do with the oil is up to them.=
=E2=80=9DLogically then the activists should go to the customers and say =
=E2=80=9Cyou also should be net zero emitters,=E2=80=9D and obviously to so=
me extent they do =E2=80=94=C2=A0big tech companies and airlines and utilit=
ies and others get plenty of climate pressure and often go around committin=
g to becoming net zero emitters eventually =E2=80=94=C2=A0but there are so =
many more users of fossil fuels than there are producers, and their fossil-=
fuel use is generally=C2=A0less salient. The investors in an enterprise sof=
tware company or direct-to-consumer retail brand or whatever might=C2=A0car=
e=C2=A0about the environment, but it will be pretty far down their list of =
concerns=C2=A0about that company. Whereas at an oil major, from now until 2=
050, climate is always going to dominate the discussion.So in a world where=
 you can be a =E2=80=9Cnet zero emitter=E2=80=9D through some combination o=
f (1) emitting lots of carbon and (2) buying somewhat abstract carbon offse=
ts to get your total carbon to sum to zero, the highest bidders for those o=
ffsets will be the companies where carbon emissions are most salient. The c=
ost to a public=C2=A0oil major of emitting lots of carbon =E2=80=94=C2=A0in=
 terms of investor complaints, proxy fights, higher cost of capital, etc. =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0is high, so the value of getting to net zero is high. Wherea=
s at a software company the salience is lower, so the cost is lower, so the=
 value is lower. The oil companies want to shift emissions from themselves =
to their customers because the emissions are=C2=A0cheaper=C2=A0for the cust=
omers.
