<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Bank debt</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One stylized fact about the current ec=
onomy is that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2547=
2439.275794/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjA=
tMDQtMDIvYmFua3MtaGF2ZS10b28tbXVjaC1tb25leS1ub3c_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTAyNjIxX01PTk=
VZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09M=
jExMDI2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3ab16b07" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;"> banks have too much money</a>. People and companies have lots of c=
ash and want to store it somewhere, so they put it in bank deposits. Becaus=
e they have so much cash, they do not need to borrow much cash, so there is=
 not a ton of demand for bank loans. Banks are left with lots of deposits a=
nd no loans to invest them in. They dislike this situation and try to avoid=
 it by, for instance, lowering interest rates on deposits below zero, or ju=
st <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25472439.275794=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9iYW5rcy10by1jb21wYW5pZXMtbm8tbW9yZS=
1kZXBvc2l0cy1wbGVhc2UtMTE2MjMyMzgyMDA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB55ade292" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">asking customers to cool it with the deposits</a>. But there is only =
so much they can do.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Two important stylized=
 facts about bank deposits are (1) they can be withdrawn at any time and (2=
) a dollar in the bank has to always be worth a dollar. If you have money i=
n a checking account, you can go to the bank and ask for it back, and they =
have to be able to give it to you in full immediately. If they can=E2=80=99=
t, then the banking system is in bad trouble. This is the =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=
=99s a Wonderful Life=E2=80=9D problem, and modern banking regulation is de=
signed to prevent it. In particular:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decim=
al; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px=
;">There is=C2=A0<em>capital=C2=A0regulation</em>=C2=A0(as well as =E2=80=
=9Csupplementary leverage ratio=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25472439.275794/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmlzLm9=
yZy9mc2kvZnNpc3VtbWFyaWVzL3RsYWMucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBae318092" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">total loss-absorbing capacity</a>=E2=80=9D rules), which requires ban=
ks to fund a certain percentage of their assets with shareholders=E2=80=99 =
equity (or bonds, for TLAC) so that, if the assets lose value, the sharehol=
ders lose money first and the depositors are protected.</li>=09<li style=3D=
"margin-bottom: 5px;">There are=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/25472439.275794/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cub2NjLmdvdi9uZXdzLWlzc3Vh=
bmNlcy9idWxsZXRpbnMvMjAyMS9idWxsZXRpbi0yMDIxLTkuaHRtbCM6fjp0ZXh0PVRoZSUyME5=
TRlIlMkMlMjBhJTIwcXVhbnRpdGF0aXZlJTIwbGlxdWlkaXR5LGJ5JTIwdGhlJTIwYWdlbmNpZX=
MlMjBpbiUyMDIwMTQu/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7858ffa8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"><em>net stabl=
e funding=C2=A0</em>rules</a>, which, to oversimplify, require banks to fun=
d a certain percentage of their assets with=C2=A0<em>long-term=C2=A0</em>ob=
ligations (stock, bonds, etc.) so that they don=E2=80=99t get asked for all=
 of their money back at once.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These r=
ules make a lot of sense in an =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a Wonderful Life=E2=80=
=9D world, or in the world of the 2008 financial crisis, when banks had thi=
n capital cushions and lots of short-term non-deposit liabilities (repo, et=
c.) that led to surprising bank-run-type situations.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">But these rules are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/25472439.275794/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL25ld3N=
sZXR0ZXJzLzIwMjAtMDUtMjEvbW9uZXktc3R1ZmYtdG9vLW11Y2gtbW9uZXktY2FuLWJlLWJhZC=
1mb3ItYmFua3M_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTAyNjIxX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1d=
G1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjExMDI2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0=
dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc070edde" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a little weird</a> in a wor=
ld where people keep shoveling cash into bank deposits and banks, not havin=
g enough loans to make,=C2=A0shovel the cash into Treasury securities or re=
serves at the Federal Reserve. One reason that they=E2=80=99re weird is tha=
t, when a bank gets $100 of deposits and puts the $100 into Fed reserves, i=
ts risk (of a capital loss or bank run) hasn=E2=80=99t really gone up any, =
so it=E2=80=99s weird that these risk-mitigating measures kick in.[3]</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But another reason they=E2=80=99re weird is that=
, when banks get too much money, that=C2=A0<em>forces them to raise more mo=
ney</em>. If you have a bank with assets consisting of $100 of loans and li=
abilities of $10 of equity capital (10% of assets), $10 of long-term bonds =
(20% long-term funding including equity and bonds),=C2=A0and $80 of deposit=
s, and then all of a sudden you get $300 more of deposits and park them in =
Treasuries, now your equity capital is only 2.5% of assets and you are unde=
rcapitalized and need to sell stock, and your long-term funding ratio is al=
so too low and you need to sell some bonds.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/25472439.275794/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9iYW5rcy1kZWJ0L=
XNhbGVzLWFyZS1kcml2aW5nLXRoZS1jb3Jwb3JhdGUtYm9uZC1tYXJrZXQtMTE2MzUyNDA2MDE_=
bW9kPWhwX2xlYWRfcG9zMg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBff4a4c5c" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">fun Wall =
Street Journal story</a> about how banks are rushing to issue bonds because=
 they have too much money:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">U.S.=
 banks are overrun with cash. So they are loading up on debt. =E2=80=A6</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The record debt sales might seem unnecessary b=
ecause banks are already up to their eyeballs in cash. The biggest consumer=
 and commercial banks have collected trillions of dollars of deposits since=
 the pandemic started.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But deposits are onl=
y one part of the liability equation for the biggest banks. They are also r=
equired to keep a certain share of their liabilities in long-term debt. Bec=
ause of that, the ratio of debt to other liabilities can get out of whack w=
hen deposits grow as much as they have. So banks are issuing more bonds to =
navigate the regulatory hurdles.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Requiremen=
ts that long-term debt make up a minimum share of banks=E2=80=99 liabilitie=
s is a consequence of regulations after the financial crisis of 2008-09. Th=
e idea is that a layer of long-term debt makes banks less susceptible to pa=
nic in short-term funding markets, which was a key reason for the demise of=
 Lehman Brothers.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As problems =
with the banking system go, =E2=80=9Cbanks have too much money so they have=
 to raise more money=E2=80=9D is considerably nicer than the more tradition=
al and=C2=A0scarier =E2=80=9Cbanks have too little money so they have to ra=
ise more money.=E2=80=9D This is more of a weird problem than a bad problem=
. It is weird though.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-flex-ad" border=3D"0" c=
ellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" align=3D"center">
<tr>
